WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6 New York English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:18.000
And I'm Beth. In Britain, we call them crisps and you might know them as potato chips

5
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:25.000
But whatever you call them, these fried potato slices are probably the world's favourite snack

6
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Neil, are you a big crisps eater and what's your favourite flavour?

7
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I love crisps, Beth. They are my favourite snack

8
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.000
My favourite flavour is prawn cocktail, which is controversial because a lot of people don't like that flavour

9
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I think my favourite is salt and vinegar

10
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Yummy, you make me hungry

11
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Well crisps might be popular but with lots of oil and salt, they're not the healthiest food

12
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:54.000
So why do we love them so much? That's what BBC World Service program the food chain wanted to find

13
00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.000
out. Here, presenter Ruth Alexander talks to Mitchell Dingwell, her food executive

14
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
responsible for developing new crisps flavours

15
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Why do we love crisps so much?

16
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
I think it's just that crunch rate, you can't beat the crunch in the net

17
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Delicious, salty feeling in your mouth and it just becomes a snowball effect. You just want more of it

18
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
For Mitchell, the best thing about crisps is the loud crunch

19
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
He says you can't beat it, an idiom meaning something like that's the best thing and you

20
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.000
won't find anything better

21
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Mitchell says once you started eating crisps, it's hard to stop

22
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
and you just want to eat more and more. He calls this a snowball effect

23
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
A situation where doing something causes other similar things to happen

24
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
You eat one crisps and before you know it, the whole package gone

25
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
In this episode, we'll be visiting two countries in love with crisps

26
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
and as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases

27
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
all of which you can find on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

28
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
But first, I have a question for you, Beth

29
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.000
The record for the world's largest packet of crisps was recently broken in Saudi Arabia

30
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:14.000
but how much did the packet weigh? Was it A about 1.5 tons? B about 2.5 tons

31
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:24.000
or C about 3.5 tons? Okay, wow, they are all huge. I'm going to guess about 3.5 tons

32
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Okay, we'll find out the answer later

33
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Let's travel first to Singapore home of JoLineEng

34
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
A market research analyst who specializes in salty snacks

35
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
Here's JoLine talking with Ruth Alexander for BBC program The Food Chain

36
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Is the potato chip the most popular of all salty snacks? It's very very much dependent on personal preference

37
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
But if I were to look at certain countries, you could see like in the UK it's very much

38
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.000
part and parcel of like you don't have it only during snack times you have it with lunch as well

39
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
You put it, my husband's from UK and he kind of put it in his sandwich as well

40
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
sandwich with a crisp inside oh yeah, that's great exactly

41
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:12.000
JoLine says the popularity of different snacks depends on personal preference

42
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:18.000
Someone's subjective liking or disliking for something based on their personal opinion

43
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
In some places crisps are part and parcel of everyday life

44
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Part and parcel means to be an essential element or feature of something

45
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:30.000
In Britain crisps are so essential that people even eat crisps sandwiches

46
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
But not everywhere is so in love with potato chips

47
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Let's meet Jenny Martinis, a food blogger from Mexico

48
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:44.000
In Mexico, tortilla corn chips are eaten instead of potato chips

49
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And it's common to see street vendors selling bags of corn tortillas filled with different sources

50
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Here Jenny tells Ruth Alexander more for BBC World Service program The Food Chain

51
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
For you, which is your go-to snack that tortilla chips or the potato chips?

52
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Definitely the tortilla chip. Why?

53
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Because you could do so many things dip it in almost everything adding some Waka molly

54
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Spicy salsa or just sour cream with a mixture of chipotle sauce

55
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Ruth asks if tortillas are Jenny's go-to snack

56
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:28.000
You can use the phrase go-to to describe something which is relied upon to be the best thing for a particular purpose

57
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
For example for a lot of people Wikipedia is the go-to website for online information

58
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And Jenny thinks corn tortillas are especially good with guacamole

59
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
A paste made of mashed avocado which sounds delicious

60
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
And maybe a little healthier than a British crisp sandwich

61
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Speaking of which what was the answer to your question Neil?

62
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
I asked you how heavy the world's largest bag of crisps was

63
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And I said very heavy over three and a half tons

64
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Well, it's not that big but the real answer is still enormous about 1.5 tons

65
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
The bag made in re-ad was 9 meters tall

66
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with the phrase you can't beat that

67
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Meaning that something is the best and you won't find anything better

68
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
A snowball effect is a situation where one action causes other similar actions to happen

69
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Someone's personal preference is their subjective liking or disliking for something based on their own opinion

70
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:37.000
To be part and parcel of something means to be an essential or integral feature of it

71
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And something which is described as the go-to can be relied upon as the best thing for a particular situation

72
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And finally guacamole is a paste made of mashed avocado, lime juice and salt delicious

73
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Once again, our six minutes are up

74
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.000
But if you're hungry for more then head over to our website

75
